{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1817"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.03,0.07,0.65,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1817"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"927"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2585"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"6452"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27701"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, nausea, vomiting and lower abdominal pain. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and takes metformin. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There is mild tenderness in the suprapubic region and right renal angle tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine microscopy shows pyuria and Gram negative rods. Treatment is started with intravenous amoxicillin and gentamicin. \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E - sensitive to this antibiotic combination - is isolated from urine and blood cultures collected on admission. On the third day of hospitalisation she remains febrile and the flank tenderness is more pronounced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for her continued fever?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinary tract obstruction","Drug-related fever","Enterohaemorrhagic Escherichia coli infection","Pyonephrosis","Co-infection in a system unrelated to the genitourinary tract"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of complicated pyelonephritis that has not responded to appropriate antibiotic therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EPyonephrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for her continued fever. This describes a collection of pus in the renal pelvis as a result of pyelonephritis with consequent urinary tract obstruction. The diagnosis is supported by her ongoing suprapubic and flank tenderness with fever, hypotension, borderline tachycardia and growth of \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E that has not responded to antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E in itself is not the most likely explanation for her continued fever; rather, it is a crucial precipitant in the development of pyonephrosis. The obstruction leads to stasis of infected urine and subsequent accumulation of pus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterohaemorrhagic Escherichia coli infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bloody diarrhoea and abdominal pain. While this patient has \u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E infection, the clinical picture is clearly that of urosepsis rather than enteric infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eco-infection in a system unrelated to the genitourinary tract\u003C/strong\u003E must be considered given the possibility of bacteraemia leading to seeding of other organs, the patient has ongoing flank tenderness, suggesting a complication related to her pyelonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-related fever\u003C/strong\u003E is always a possibility, however given she has ongoing flank tenderness, a cause for her fever related to her initial presentation is more likely and should be excluded prior to accepting a drug-induced fever as the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPyonephrosis is a surgical emergency requiring urgent drainage, typically via percutaneous nephrostomy, in addition to continued antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pyonephrosis must be considered when fever persists despite appropriate antibiotics in pyelonephritis.","Ongoing flank tenderness with fever despite appropriate antibiotics suggests a complicated urinary tract infection requiring imaging.","Pyonephrosis requires urgent surgical drainage in addition to antibiotics."],"references":["Ludvigson AE, Beaule LT. Urologic Emergencies. Surg Clin North Am. 2016; 96:407-24."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66269"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T20:30:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T20:32:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1817"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRe